<h2>Teaching Philosophy (English)</h2>

<p>I am Alexander Kilpatrick, this page outlines my approach to teaching and assessment.</p>

<h3>Core Goal</h3>
<p>My primary goal as an educator is to teach course material effectively and to assess student learning as fairly as possible. Fairness means consistency: the same rules apply to everyone, without exception.</p>

<h3>Deadlines and Rules</h3>
<p>I adhere strictly to course deadlines and to the rules of the University of Aizu. Late submissions, missed assessments, and absences are handled according to the policies stated in the course syllabus. I do not grant personal exceptions — strict adherence to policy is the fairest way to treat all students equally.</p>

<h3>Excused Absences and Official Accommodations</h3>
<p>I fully respect the university's official accommodation process. If you have a legitimate reason for an absence — for example, illness documented by a medical certificate submitted to the Student Affairs Academic Affairs Division (学生課教務係) — I am bound by their determination. Where the university recommends an adjustment, I will follow that recommendation. No adjustments will be made outside of this process.</p>

<h3>Communication</h3>
<p>I am always happy to discuss course content, assignment feedback, or questions about the material. However, if you are dealing with a situation that may affect your attendance or performance, the right first step is to contact Student Affairs (学生課教務係) directly. I cannot pre-approve exceptions, but I will honour whatever the university determines.</p>

